    {
      "id": "tpt-whygraphs",
      "type": "markdown",
      "label": "Why Graphs?",
      "position": {
        "x": -200,
        "y": -180
      },
      "width": 560,
      "height": 560,
      "visible": true,
      "showLabel": true,
      "data": {
        "markdown": "## Why Node Graphs?\n\n*Because anything is possible on a node graph on the web.*\n\n### Graphs Are a Universal Canvas\nA node can be **anything**: text, code, data, UI, API, AI model, video, live query. An edge can mean **anything**: flows into, depends on, triggers, contains.\n\nThere's no schema to fight. No format to escape. **You decide what nodes and edges mean.**\n\n### Graphs Are Executable\nThis isn't just visualization — nodes can **run code**, call APIs, stream data, respond to events. The graph isn't a picture of your system. **The graph IS your system.**\n\n### The Browser Is the Runtime\nNo install. No deploy. Share a URL and it runs. The entire web platform — fetch, canvas, websockets, workers — is your execution environment.\n\n### Infinite Extensibility\nToday: markdown, shapes, links.\nTomorrow: live database nodes, AI inference nodes, video players, form builders, dashboards.\n\n**Plugins add new node types.** The platform grows without limits.\n\n### Composition All the Way Down\nGraphs can contain graphs. Nodes can expose ports. Build primitives, compose them into systems, share them as templates.\n\n**Graphs are the new code.**",
        "_classBinding": {
          "key": "markdown",
          "sourceRef": "/library/classes/nodes/markdown.node-class.node",
          "ref": "/library/classes/nodes/markdown.node-class.node",
          "identity": {
